ce:section.ce:para:
Fig. 9 shows the overall thermal resistance Rt (Eq. 15) as a function of the characteristic fluid temperature, Tc. The 3 tiers identified are clearer and separate in order. Two key trends appear. First, every fluid shows a decline in Rt with higher liquid temperature of approximately 20–30% from 20°C to 60°C. This is because dynamic viscosity decays exponentially with temperature, while thermal conductivity (k) and expansion coefficient (β) change far less. This confirms that viscosity is the dominant antagonist identified in the sensitivity sweep. Second, the ordering of the fluids remains largely invariant with temperature, indicating that the relative differences in the thermophysical properties between fluids outweigh their variation over the operational temperature window (Eq. 5). For example, silicon oil 20 cSt never overtakes silicon oil 5 cSt. Among commercial products in the study which form tiers 2 and 3, selecting a top-tier commercial coolant (Tier 2, 6 K/W) over a lower-tier commercial option (Tier 3, 7 - 8 K/W) lowers thermal resistance by around 17–33%, underscoring the importance of optimal coolant choice at the system level. Notably, all Tier 1 fluids are candidate chemistries, where their 5 K/W performance represents a 15–20% improvement against the commercial products in tier 2, indicating headroom for new formulations via compositional tuning. Fig. 9 demonstrates that selecting an intrinsically low viscosity fluid is more influential than relying on thermal thinning during operation, a practical guideline for data center design where inlet temperatures are constrained by reliability considerations. However, in pumped SPIC, the heat transfer coefficient scales with fluid thermal conductivity (
h = Nu ˑ k / L
); thus, coolants with high thermal conductivity are expected to outperform even the top-tier commercial products under forced flow conditions.
